    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Velocity Calculator</h2>
      <p>This calculator solves the fundamental equation of motion: <strong>v = d / t</strong>. Select which variable you want to solve for, enter the two known values, and the calculator instantly computes the third. Whether you need to find how fast something moves, how far it travels, or how long a journey takes, this tool gives you the answer in real time.</p>

      <p>The velocity formula is one of the most widely used equations in physics and everyday life. It applies to anything from calculating driving times and running pace to analyzing the speed of light or the orbital velocity of satellites. By rearranging the same equation, you can solve for any of the three variables: velocity, distance, or time.</p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>The Velocity Formula</h2>
      <p>The three forms of the velocity equation are:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>v = d / t</strong> — Velocity equals distance divided by time</li>
        <li><strong>d = v x t</strong> — Distance equals velocity multiplied by time</li>
        <li><strong>t = d / v</strong> — Time equals distance divided by velocity</li>
      </ul>
      <p>These formulas calculate average velocity over the entire distance. If the speed varies during the journey, the result represents the mean speed required to cover the given distance in the given time.</p>

      <h3>Velocity vs. Acceleration</h3>
      <p>Velocity describes how fast an object moves at a given moment or on average. Acceleration describes how quickly the velocity itself changes over time. A car maintaining 60 km/h has constant velocity and zero acceleration. A car speeding up from 0 to 100 km/h is accelerating. This calculator handles constant or average velocity scenarios. For problems involving acceleration, see our Force Calculator.</p>

      <h3>Unit Conversions</h3>
      <p>When using this calculator, make sure your units are consistent. If distance is in meters and time in seconds, velocity will be in meters per second (m/s). To convert: 1 m/s = 3.6 km/h, 1 mph = 1.609 km/h, and 1 knot = 1.852 km/h. Keeping units consistent is the most common source of errors in physics calculations.</p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is the formula for velocity?</h3>
      <p>Velocity is calculated using the formula v = d / t, where v is velocity (speed), d is the distance traveled, and t is the time taken. This gives you the average velocity over the distance covered.</p>

      <h3>What is the difference between speed and velocity?</h3>
      <p>Speed is a scalar quantity that measures how fast an object moves regardless of direction. Velocity is a vector quantity that includes both magnitude (speed) and direction. In everyday calculations without direction, speed and velocity are often used interchangeably.</p>

      <h3>What units are used for velocity?</h3>
      <p>Velocity is commonly measured in meters per second (m/s) in the metric system or miles per hour (mph) in the imperial system. Other common units include kilometers per hour (km/h), feet per second (ft/s), and knots for nautical applications.</p>

      <h3>How do you find distance from velocity and time?</h3>
      <p>Multiply velocity by time: d = v x t. For example, if an object moves at 10 m/s for 5 seconds, the distance traveled is 10 x 5 = 50 meters.</p>

      <h3>How do you find time from distance and velocity?</h3>
      <p>Divide the distance by the velocity: t = d / v. For example, if you need to travel 100 km at 50 km/h, the time required is 100 / 50 = 2 hours.</p>
    </article>

